                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d489">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1334: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Standley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kuibyshev</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-22T18:00:00+04:00"
                            >May 22, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 22—4:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>432. Department’s 217, May 9, 8 [<hi rend="italic">7</hi>] p.m. I endeavored to
                    impress upon Vyshinski<note n="4" xml:id="d489fn4">Soviet Assistant Commissar
                        for Foreign Affairs.</note> yesterday the hope of my Government that the
                    Soviet Government would do everything possible to facilitate the movement of
                    supplies to China through the Soviet Union. Vyshinski stated that he was not
                    fully acquainted with all the details of the problem but would willingly inform
                    the interested Soviet authorities of the concern of the American Government in
                    the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Standley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
